1
00:00:00,368 --> 00:00:26,780
Namo Tassa Bhagavato Arahato Sambha Sambuddhasa Namo Tassa Bhagavato Arahato Sambha Sambuddhasa Namo Tassa Bhagavato Arahato Sambha Sambuddhasa

2
00:00:27,757 --> 00:00:39,631
Homage to the Buddha, the blessed, noble and fully self-enlightened one.

3
00:00:39,651 --> 00:00:53,746
So for one or two who have just joined us, I've been over these past few weeks going through the Buddha's life and using it as a sort of basis to consider his teachings and

4
00:00:55,920 --> 00:01:14,688
and we finally come now to the years of teaching and his final hours his final days so if we recall to mind on that wonderful during that wonderful night he became enlightened with the dawn he

5
00:01:15,310 --> 00:01:17,974
That's how they put it, in the full moon of May.

6
00:01:18,013 --> 00:01:28,489
And he became fully awakened and understood exactly why he had been in a state of dissatisfaction or suffering.

7
00:01:28,510 --> 00:01:37,183
And he spent the next night or so considering the Dharma and going through especially the Wheel of Dependent Origination, which is the...

8
00:01:37,787 --> 00:01:49,879
which was his psychological paradigm as to why we get ourselves into such a dreadful state and then after that his first thought was who can I teach?

9
00:01:50,319 --> 00:01:51,641
who can I pass this on to?

10
00:01:53,423 --> 00:02:06,275
and then came the doubt that people weren't there wasn't anybody who could think of that really would be open to this so if you consider that at that time

11
00:02:08,044 --> 00:02:13,895
All the philosophies, all the understandings were all about the self.

12
00:02:14,254 --> 00:02:16,618
They were about, did the self annihilate?

13
00:02:16,699 --> 00:02:24,872
So there were some people who just presumed that when you died you annihilated, would be equal to our materialists.

14
00:02:25,653 --> 00:02:32,044
There were those who believed in some sort of future life, rebirth, but eventually you would annihilate them.

15
00:02:32,918 --> 00:02:40,090
There were those who thought that actually that's all you did, you just kept being reborn and there was not much you could do about it, it was just the way it was.

16
00:02:41,111 --> 00:02:50,168
And there were some who were so convinced of that that they said, one teacher said, if you went down to one side of the Ganges and...

17
00:02:50,147 --> 00:03:15,159
did all sorts of compassionate and wonderful deeds and came up the other side burning, murdering and thieving it wouldn't make a jot of difference your karmic line is already set it was fated and there's nothing you can do so all the philosophies around that time were to do with the self and what happens to the self

18
00:03:16,354 --> 00:03:32,689
So when he suddenly realized that this self that they were talking about was a phantasm, they didn't actually exist, it was just a concept in the mind, then as he's thinking, well, who can I get this message across to, then he gets this block.

19
00:03:33,290 --> 00:03:35,151
This is my own interpretation, you understand that.

20
00:03:36,432 --> 00:03:45,822
And so it says in the scriptures that the great Brahma Sahampati came and said, no, Lord, do teach that some people with only a little dust in their eyes

21
00:03:47,218 --> 00:03:52,487
Now, we can either, you know, these days we'd be rather cynical of Brahma's amputee turning up.

22
00:03:52,508 --> 00:03:54,811
It's more in the sense that he had a second thought about it.

23
00:03:55,712 --> 00:04:00,681
But you must remember that there's always a little bit of propaganda in the Buddhist texts.

24
00:04:00,700 --> 00:04:05,389
And Brahman, of course, is the highest of all gods in the Hindu pantheon.

25
00:04:05,788 --> 00:04:12,920
And that he should be coming down and asking the Buddha to teach was simply saying that the Buddha had gone beyond the teachings of his day.

26
00:04:13,602 --> 00:04:13,681
Hmm?

27
00:04:14,437 --> 00:04:18,745
So, leaving that aside, he then decides to teach.

28
00:04:18,785 --> 00:04:32,165
Now, there are some writers whom you'll come across who said that he hesitated to teach, that he could have just sat there and simply done nothing, just sat in bliss until the body gave up.

29
00:04:33,928 --> 00:04:37,915
But this, in a sense, goes completely contrary to his own teachings.

30
00:04:39,041 --> 00:04:43,747
The Eightfold Path, that we call the Eightfold Path, is one path.

31
00:04:45,709 --> 00:04:55,742
We can think of it as a highway with eight lanes in it, but I think we're closer to the mark if we think of a tightrope made of eight strands, because it's so easy to fall off.

32
00:04:56,622 --> 00:04:59,165
And that's how we find it's difficult to walk the path.

33
00:05:00,067 --> 00:05:02,670
So these eight strands move together.

34
00:05:02,910 --> 00:05:07,716
It's not possible in the Buddha's teaching to separate out

35
00:05:07,814 --> 00:05:13,041
right understanding from its expression in action, in what we do.

36
00:05:13,942 --> 00:05:17,928
So wisdom will naturally express itself into compassion.

37
00:05:18,249 --> 00:05:32,370
That's the whole point, that there's a flow downward and outward, downward, inward, into the very heart of our existence, of our being, for want of a better word, where once we've understood such things,

38
00:05:32,350 --> 00:05:35,317
then of course there's that change of attitude in the heart.

39
00:05:35,336 --> 00:05:40,629
So that's why in the Eightfold Path we go from right understanding to right attitude.

40
00:05:40,649 --> 00:05:45,077
And right understanding is always about these three characteristics.

41
00:05:45,218 --> 00:05:47,805
It's always about understanding the role of desire.

42
00:05:48,165 --> 00:05:51,151
It's always about undercutting the idea of self.

43
00:05:52,076 --> 00:06:01,411
And when that translates, of course, that idea translates into the heart, then it manifests as an outward going, an outward going.

44
00:06:01,430 --> 00:06:07,158
So when he talks about himself as a teacher, the word he uses is anu kampan.

45
00:06:07,199 --> 00:06:13,848
He says, I as a teacher have done everything that a teacher could do for you out of compassion.

46
00:06:13,829 --> 00:06:24,471
But the word isn't the usual word karuna, which we've come across, but anukampan, which means moving towards the other, moving towards the other, an empathy, a sympathy.

47
00:06:24,891 --> 00:06:28,619
And that's what drives him to teach.

48
00:06:33,910 --> 00:06:35,213
So we can say that...

49
00:06:36,442 --> 00:06:48,975
When the self goes, or as the self goes, we begin to understand this idea, this understanding of interdependency, interconnections, all that sort of stuff.

50
00:06:48,995 --> 00:06:55,201
But of course when that goes into the heart, that expresses itself in love, compassion, sympathetic joy.

51
00:06:55,942 --> 00:07:05,132
If it doesn't do that, then it can remain as an idea, as a notion,

52
00:07:05,415 --> 00:07:34,831
but it's not going to affect our behavior until it moves into the heart now in the Zen tradition they will tell you that compassion arises naturally with wisdom and I think we can take that as fairly true but even so we should budget along a bit because sometimes we can stay up in the head a bit too long when it moves into the heart and we are in communication with people then that naturally expresses itself by the way we speak

53
00:07:35,470 --> 00:07:57,629
kindly, appropriately and all that and how we behave in a gentle manner things like that not getting angry and killing people and in our livelihood so you can see there's an outward flow so there's the Buddha he's had this amazing insight he's suddenly understood something to which there is no further profundity

54
00:07:58,065 --> 00:08:07,697
And he's thinking about it, and he's worked it through, and as it drops into the heart, there's that movement outward of, who can I bring to this sort of liberation?

55
00:08:09,778 --> 00:08:13,182
The doubt isn't whether he should do it or not.

56
00:08:13,262 --> 00:08:15,605
The doubt is whether people are ready for it.

57
00:08:16,206 --> 00:08:19,490
And once he's overcome that, he moves forward.

58
00:08:19,629 --> 00:08:23,634
So the first two that come to mind are his old teachers.

59
00:08:23,682 --> 00:08:29,651
Because they trained him and he knew their religious and spiritual depth.

60
00:08:30,694 --> 00:08:32,717
But they died.

61
00:08:33,217 --> 00:08:39,089
And when I was in Burma last, there was a statue which I'd never seen before, the actual mudra, the shape of it.

62
00:08:39,710 --> 00:08:44,037
And the Buddha was sitting there and his hand was pointing like that towards the heart centre.

63
00:08:44,572 --> 00:08:46,416
I'd never seen it before and asked what it was.

64
00:08:47,596 --> 00:08:57,432
I was rather touched when they said that it was the sadness he felt when he realised his two teachers were dead and he wasn't able to pass on the message of his teachings.

65
00:08:58,493 --> 00:09:01,197
I thought it was rather touching.

66
00:09:01,216 --> 00:09:06,504
Then the next people he thought about, of course, were his own five companions.

67
00:09:07,265 --> 00:09:13,634
So he walks, it's about 100 and odd miles from where he was up to Isiputama Park, perhaps a little more,

68
00:09:13,936 --> 00:09:17,202
and finds them there, and that's where he begins his teaching.

69
00:09:18,184 --> 00:09:28,687
So, even we ourselves, you see, we have to accept that once you're on the path, whether you like it or not, you become a teacher.

70
00:09:28,971 --> 00:09:38,326
It might not be an official post, and you might not get paid for it, but you're immediately there as an exemplar, you see.

71
00:09:38,767 --> 00:09:55,873
So, I think I've mentioned before that if you tell somebody that you meditate, and that it's done you a powerful lot of good, and then they find you completely drunk in the gutter, then they have second thoughts about whether they want to do any of this meditation.

72
00:09:55,852 --> 00:10:05,802
So as soon as we take on a path, whether we like it or not, we have the responsibility of being as best we can an exemplar.

73
00:10:05,923 --> 00:10:07,668
And by that way, we are a teacher.

74
00:10:09,403 --> 00:10:26,653
so that question that you'll see discussed in various books as far as I'm concerned there is no doubt about the Buddha's desire to pass on the message the compassion must come forward

75
00:10:27,780 --> 00:10:45,684
When we look at the other tradition, that is the Pacheco Buddha, the Buddha who's a private Buddha, in other words somebody who simply becomes enlightened, it's not that they don't want to teach, the idea is that they can't, they don't have that ability, something that has to be learned.

76
00:10:46,405 --> 00:10:48,207
And this comes out in the Buddha himself.

77
00:10:48,528 --> 00:10:57,399
So he's now got up from his seat and he's off searching his disciples and he comes across a Samana, another ascetic.

78
00:10:57,750 --> 00:11:02,798
And the ascetic looks at him and says, you look very bright, you look very clear.

79
00:11:03,337 --> 00:11:04,158
Who's your teacher?

80
00:11:04,480 --> 00:11:11,208
And the Buddha announces, I have no teacher, I'm the fully enlightened being, I know the cosmos in and out and so on and so forth.

81
00:11:11,909 --> 00:11:16,395
And the ascetic simply says, oh no, shakes his head and moves on.

82
00:11:16,416 --> 00:11:20,581
So he obviously learnt very quickly that's not quite the way that you teach somebody.

83
00:11:21,942 --> 00:11:22,003
So,

84
00:11:23,434 --> 00:11:25,958
So then you'll see that in the scriptures.

85
00:11:26,019 --> 00:11:35,251
If you read the early parts of the scriptures, like the Nipata Sutta, it's not so formalized, four of these, ten of those, twelve of them.

86
00:11:35,972 --> 00:11:37,815
It's very personal.

87
00:11:38,856 --> 00:11:46,067
You can see that they are memories of actual conversations that he's had with people.

88
00:11:46,267 --> 00:11:53,054
And it's only as he's teaching and as people come to him and want to remember what he's teaching that these mnemonics are worked out.

89
00:11:53,535 --> 00:11:59,143
So it's easy to remember if there are five of these and four of those and 37 factors of enlightenment.

90
00:11:59,163 --> 00:12:00,063
So that sort of thing.

91
00:12:00,865 --> 00:12:10,856
And of course by the end of his life it was beginning to turn into almost an academic exercise which later on turned into the Abhidhamma.

92
00:12:12,052 --> 00:12:41,804
so the teaching was just part and parcel of his nature and when you go through his life there's all sorts of incidents that happen and I only covered a few but just the sense of his teaching so there was one very dull monk who was so dull that he couldn't it said that as he remembered one phrase it pushed the other phrase out

93
00:12:43,134 --> 00:13:08,687
so he never got beyond this one phrase and his brother said to him that you know really he wasn't fit to be in the order because a part of it was trying to remember the Buddha's teaching he couldn't remember the Buddha's teaching what the heck would he do so when the Buddha heard about this he went to visit and immediately gave him an exercise of just rubbing a piece just actually taking a piece of clean cloth

94
00:13:08,667 --> 00:13:19,140
wiping his face, the sweat on his face, and rubbing the cloth, and simply saying, Anicca, impermanence, impermanence.

95
00:13:19,160 --> 00:13:24,268
And lo and betide, in no shorter time, as the scriptures say, he became fully liberated.

96
00:13:25,169 --> 00:13:32,298
The gloss on that, the gloss on these in no length of time, in the commentaries, is around about 25 to 30 years.

97
00:13:32,679 --> 00:13:37,206
So it's not as though he just wiped his face a few times and bingo.

98
00:13:39,024 --> 00:13:42,850
So, I don't know whether you ever want to try that.

99
00:13:43,032 --> 00:13:45,296
It didn't work for me.

100
00:13:45,316 --> 00:13:55,452
So it's a case of understanding that he has this ability to, the teacher has a marvelous ability to actually get into the person and just catch what they want.

101
00:13:56,073 --> 00:13:59,919
Another one is, of course, the very famous story of Angulimala.

102
00:14:00,423 --> 00:14:03,485
So Angulimalaism is a murderer of sorts.

103
00:14:03,566 --> 00:14:14,759
He's actually, according to the story, he's actually fulfilling a demand made of him by his teacher who was jealous of him, fearful of him taking over his position.

104
00:14:15,440 --> 00:14:26,532
And he demanded of him as his guru reward, in fact you give a present to your guru in those days, that he collect, so to say, a thousand little fingers.

105
00:14:26,865 --> 00:14:51,101
and off he goes and does that and at some point the Buddha either meets him by chance or he's heard about him or through his powers understands that Angulimala is not a murderer in his heart he's just been driven to this and I wouldn't be surprised if he knew of him because he was supposed to be a Brahmin he was of a Brahmin caste

106
00:14:51,958 --> 00:15:18,168
and so the tale goes when Angulimala spies him and starts to hunt him down the Buddha produces this magical trick of walking and yet always staying ahead of Angulimala who's racing and racing trying to catch up then when Angulimala shouts out stop monk or stop ascetic the Buddha turns around and says well I have stopped it's you that haven't stopped

107
00:15:18,149 --> 00:15:24,562
And somehow that just cuts into Angulimala and makes him consider what he's actually doing.

108
00:15:25,384 --> 00:15:33,643
And presumably in the following conversations with the Buddha, he recognizes that he's fallen foul of...

109
00:15:33,623 --> 00:16:01,302
of his own heart by following a tradition of giving a present to the guru even though that present was unwholesome and again he then takes on the Buddha's teaching he becomes a member of the order which saves him from execution by the king by the way who comes looking for him and in no length of time becomes fully liberated

110
00:16:03,221 --> 00:16:06,849
The other one which is, I'm sure you all know, is Bahir of the Barcloth.

111
00:16:07,229 --> 00:16:13,441
So Bahir is a very old man and he only wears a barcloth.

112
00:16:13,461 --> 00:16:16,647
He's a long time ascetic and he's not getting anywhere.

113
00:16:16,667 --> 00:16:23,879
And he's stuck and he hears about this, the Samana, the great Samana, the great ascetic and off he goes to find the Buddha.

114
00:16:23,860 --> 00:16:40,671
So when he finds the Buddha, he says to him, you know, can you give me some teaching, can you, you know, and he wants to sit down and talk about all his issues, you know, and the Buddha says, well, this isn't the time, he says, because I'm off on alms round, you see, and Bahir of the Bath Club is.

115
00:16:40,650 --> 00:17:09,662
he's a very elderly person so he says listen I could die any minute so you know any minute I could die it's very important for me to hear any teachings you've got so the Buddha simply says to him in the seeing there's only the seeing in the hearing there's only the hearing in the cognition or in cognising there's only the cognising and right there and then Bahiya breaks through the delusion and becomes fully enlightened

116
00:17:11,515 --> 00:17:19,346
As the story goes, not long after leaving the Buddha, walking along the street, an angry cow butted him to death.

117
00:17:20,007 --> 00:17:25,134
So he was extremely lucky that the Buddha actually answered his question there and then.

118
00:17:26,476 --> 00:17:27,136
I love these stories.

119
00:17:29,480 --> 00:17:35,008
There's also another little story from Nanda, who was his half-brother.

120
00:17:35,849 --> 00:17:38,333
And he joins the order and

121
00:17:38,801 --> 00:17:44,922
And he's struggling and struggling to practice and falling into the era of over-effort.

122
00:17:45,824 --> 00:17:52,625
And in that, and realizing that he's not getting anywhere, he immediately thinks...

123
00:17:53,365 --> 00:18:09,618
which is understandable, that he's wasting his time, and he may as well leave the holy life, go back, live the good lay life, bring up some children, and hope for a better rebirth.

124
00:18:10,392 --> 00:18:29,396
So when the Buddha hears this and actually aspires and actually what's drawing him away is lust, he sends him up into the highest, he drags him up it seems into the highest heaven to see these most beautiful nymphs and setting this as a goal that he could actually attain that.

125
00:18:29,376 --> 00:18:42,300
rather than go off and just be with human women, he then carries on with his practice, and lucky for him, he also, in no length of time, becomes fully liberated.

126
00:18:43,143 --> 00:18:46,608
So there's all these lovely little stories about how...

127
00:18:46,588 --> 00:18:59,061
He was able just to, you know, really see what was necessary in a person as they approach him, see right into their heart and give them just the technique that they needed to make a break.

128
00:18:59,423 --> 00:19:03,011
And you'll see that although in the scriptures...

129
00:19:02,991 --> 00:19:31,007
you do get this idea that there's a basic technique around the breath and so on and so forth you can see from these stories that actually anything that works will do anything that brings us to some sort of realization of these three characteristics the transience how we create suffering for ourselves and the not self will do and just last one just to finish this off there's a

130
00:19:32,252 --> 00:20:02,039
his sense of humour sort of comes through of himself humour doesn't carry very well and you've got to as it were presume that this must have been a rather humorous scene what in those days if you remember there was this great idea of ascetic practice so somebody leaves the sensual world recognising that the sensual world is not going to be a place where they're going to be happy

131
00:20:02,542 --> 00:20:06,387
So they go off and they practice jhāna, so following the same path as the Buddha.

132
00:20:06,448 --> 00:20:13,056
The Buddha isn't doing anything up until he's sitting under that tree that lots of people weren't doing at that time.

133
00:20:14,377 --> 00:20:19,663
And they get into the jhāna and all that, and the happy states, and then they realize, well, that doesn't do it.

134
00:20:20,325 --> 00:20:22,807
And then the next thing is to blame the body.

135
00:20:22,968 --> 00:20:24,450
The body's at fault, so...

136
00:20:24,817 --> 00:20:27,402
So then we get into this sort of ascetic practice.

137
00:20:27,781 --> 00:20:29,724
And there was some very strange ideas.

138
00:20:29,765 --> 00:20:34,892
So if you think there's some wacko ideas going around these days, it must have been living at the time of the Buddha.

139
00:20:35,834 --> 00:20:41,541
So there are these two ascetics who are called the dog ascetic and the cow ascetic.

140
00:20:41,561 --> 00:20:50,994
And the understanding is that they're going to preempt any future rebirth as a cow or as a dog by living as a cow or as a dog right here in this very life.

141
00:20:51,903 --> 00:21:00,278
So the dog ascetic approaches the Buddha with his friend the cow ascetic and says, Lord, my friend here is practicing the cow ascetic practice.

142
00:21:01,099 --> 00:21:02,442
What will be his future?

143
00:21:02,481 --> 00:21:03,403
What will be his born?

144
00:21:03,463 --> 00:21:05,227
What happens to him when he dies?

145
00:21:05,247 --> 00:21:07,109
And the Buddha says, don't ask me.

146
00:21:08,874 --> 00:21:14,703
And his second time, the dog ascetic said, Lord, please, please don't ask me.

147
00:21:15,325 --> 00:21:21,152
And for the third time they insisted that the Lord give them some answer.

148
00:21:21,491 --> 00:21:32,045
So the Blessed One said this cow ascetic he is developing cow perceptions.

149
00:21:32,645 --> 00:21:35,148
He is developing cow feelings.

150
00:21:35,769 --> 00:21:37,590
He is developing cow consciousness.

151
00:21:37,971 --> 00:21:40,615
Therefore upon death he will be reborn as a cow.

152
00:21:42,497 --> 00:21:44,859
And the cow ascetic wept

153
00:21:45,143 --> 00:22:14,931
heavily and finally came to his senses and then having come to his senses he approaches the Lord and says blessed one my friend is practicing the dog ascetic practice and I'll leave you to finish the story so you get these lovely little instances in the scripture where obviously the Buddha is having a bit of a pulling somebody's leg so

154
00:22:15,366 --> 00:22:26,963
There was, I heard somebody say, I can't remember where that, the Buddha was only, there's only one or two incidences in the scriptures where he's actually engaged in a compassionate act.

155
00:22:27,825 --> 00:22:30,990
And in a sense that undermines the whole point of teaching.

156
00:22:31,170 --> 00:22:34,674
The teacher is, or a teacher is compassionate.

157
00:22:35,666 --> 00:22:39,612
When somebody is actually teaching anybody, that is a compassionate act.

158
00:22:39,711 --> 00:22:46,059
Whether it's a parent teaching a child or a teacher in a school or a Dharma teacher, anybody.

159
00:22:46,540 --> 00:22:50,065
Once you teach, you're offering something.

160
00:22:50,085 --> 00:22:55,531
What you're offering is your own wisdom and skills and understandings.

161
00:22:55,511 --> 00:23:09,413
So when we talk about compassionate acts, it needn't be something quite so, shall we say, so obvious as, say, serving in a leper colony or something.

162
00:23:10,536 --> 00:23:20,372
Compassionate acts can be very small and very simple and they might not need at all any sense of bravery or anything of that nature.

163
00:23:21,414 --> 00:23:32,890
So when it comes to what you might look at, what you might see as actual acts of compassion, as these days people might see it, there are just one or two.

164
00:23:32,950 --> 00:23:35,834
So remember the lovely story of Kisagotami.

165
00:23:35,953 --> 00:23:43,203
So she had lost her child and the dead child was looking around for somebody to bring it back to life or to do something for the dead child.

166
00:23:43,977 --> 00:24:02,559
And bringing it to the Buddha, he simply set her this task of finding a mustard seed, of which of course there are over plenty in India, from a house, but with the proviso that nobody had died in that house.

167
00:24:02,539 --> 00:24:10,152
So Kisargatami is in a state of desperate bereavement, leaves the child with the Buddha and goes off searching for the seed.

168
00:24:10,893 --> 00:24:13,517
And going from house to house, the message is the same.

169
00:24:13,537 --> 00:24:17,884
Sure, I've got plenty of mustard seeds, but my Lord, this house has known death.

170
00:24:17,963 --> 00:24:24,815
It's known death from who knows when, right up to this present day, so-and-so died, grandfather died, this child died, and so on.

171
00:24:25,336 --> 00:24:29,221
And very slowly it sort of dawns on her that...

172
00:24:29,201 --> 00:24:58,230
death is just part of life and this brings her to her senses and coming back to the Buddha she takes refuge in him and again later on joins the order and in no length of time becomes fully liberated there's also a lovely scene where there's a monk who's sick and the Buddha hears about this and goes to visit him and the poor man's got dysentery and he's in a dreadful state

173
00:24:58,548 --> 00:24:59,328
It's all over him.

174
00:25:00,111 --> 00:25:03,557
And he says, well, why aren't the monks helping you, you see?

175
00:25:03,917 --> 00:25:08,366
And the monk replies, well, I don't do anything for the monks, so they're not going to do anything for me.

176
00:25:09,147 --> 00:25:13,896
So the Buddha goes to the monks and says, look, this man is sick, he's dying, why aren't you doing anything for him?

177
00:25:13,916 --> 00:25:18,025
And they say, well, he doesn't do anything for us, so we won't do anything for him.

178
00:25:18,005 --> 00:25:40,333
so seeing the callousness of the monks the Buddha with Ananda go and tend to this fellow and then he gave the talk to the monks saying you know you have no mother and no father and if you don't look after each other who will and there he is he's being a nurse to this monk it's one of these little incidences which as it were brings out his humanity

179
00:25:41,613 --> 00:25:43,986
Even there on his deathbed, I mean, he's actually...

180
00:25:44,046 --> 00:25:45,776
He himself, of course, dies of dysentery.

181
00:25:46,661 --> 00:25:48,972
And he's on his deathbed and...

182
00:25:49,712 --> 00:25:57,522
presumably getting weaker and weaker, when somebody turns up, a sub-Buddha, and asks for ordination, a direct ordination from the Buddha.

183
00:25:58,044 --> 00:26:08,017
And he keeps asking, knowing that the Buddha's dying, and Ananda keeps saying, go away, this isn't the time, the Buddha's dying, come back afterwards and I'll ordain you.

184
00:26:08,597 --> 00:26:13,324
But the Buddha, on hearing this, insists that he be ordained right there and then.

185
00:26:14,096 --> 00:26:30,286
So one of the, I suppose, blessings, you might say, of the Theravada scriptures is that you really do get a feel of just an ordinary human being walking around the place and being in contact.

186
00:26:30,606 --> 00:26:37,859
There's a little tale in there where somebody walks into a room with, and he's there amongst these monks,

187
00:26:38,194 --> 00:26:43,662
And they have to ask him, which one is the blessed one, is it?

188
00:26:43,682 --> 00:26:51,311
So they get that sort of sense of orderliness, ordinariness, and just a real sense of humanity about him.

189
00:26:51,952 --> 00:27:06,952
Something which gets lost when you move into the Mahayana scriptures, where, of course, he only appears in his Sambhogakaya, the body of bliss, teaching to hundreds of thousands of bodhisattvas.

190
00:27:08,501 --> 00:27:13,229
So this brings us back to his simple, simple humanity.

191
00:27:19,837 --> 00:27:30,173
Apart from that, there's a whole business where he's actually engaged in society, in the politics of the time.

192
00:27:30,945 --> 00:27:39,880
One of the disputes that he helped to disarm was around the water rights between his own people, the Sakyas and the Kalyans.

193
00:27:40,842 --> 00:27:45,108
And he went up there to help them overcome this argument.

194
00:27:45,128 --> 00:27:49,875
They were going to enter into some sort of war or something.

195
00:27:50,577 --> 00:27:56,446
And he simply asked them what was more precious to them, the water in the river or the blood in their veins.

196
00:27:57,085 --> 00:28:05,594
There's a lovely little tale that goes with it where he asks the people who are the leaders, the warrior caste, you know, what is the fight about?

197
00:28:06,055 --> 00:28:06,996
And they're not very clear.

198
00:28:07,556 --> 00:28:12,461
And then as he comes down to strafing society, they don't quite know why they're fighting.

199
00:28:12,480 --> 00:28:13,362
They're just very angry.

200
00:28:14,002 --> 00:28:15,003
And they hate the Kaleans.

201
00:28:15,724 --> 00:28:17,287
And the Kaleans hate the others.

202
00:28:17,866 --> 00:28:21,070
And it's only when it gets down to the farmers that the farmers actually make it clear.

203
00:28:21,490 --> 00:28:23,413
Oh, we're fighting over water rights.

204
00:28:23,393 --> 00:28:29,093
And I think that has a certain resonance for these days, exactly why we're fighting.

205
00:28:29,855 --> 00:28:32,104
There's only a few people actually know why we go for war.

206
00:28:34,327 --> 00:28:52,809
There's another incident where, right towards the end of his life, where so much is happening, the king Ajatasattu wants to attack the Vajjian confederacy and sends an ambassador along to ask the Buddha whether in fact this was the right time to do it.

207
00:28:53,431 --> 00:28:54,471
It's a rather strange thing to do.

208
00:28:55,093 --> 00:29:03,643
And the Buddha actually gives him some directions as to what maintains a good society today.

209
00:29:03,623 --> 00:29:09,778
And I thought I might just read out his things, which some of them, I think, make sense to us.

210
00:29:12,484 --> 00:29:18,701
So he turns to Ananda and he says, Ananda, have you heard whether the Vajjians hold frequent and well-attended meetings?

211
00:29:19,502 --> 00:29:20,265
They do, Lord.

212
00:29:20,785 --> 00:29:24,749
As long as they do so, Ananda, they can expect to prosper and not decline.

213
00:29:25,710 --> 00:29:34,159
Have you heard whether they assemble in concord, rise in concord, and do their duty as Vajjians in concord?

214
00:29:34,179 --> 00:29:43,388
Whether they avoid enacting the unenacted or abolishing existing enactments and proceed in accordance with the ancient Vajjian laws as enacted?

215
00:29:44,028 --> 00:29:48,513
Whether they honour, respect, revere and venerate the Vajjian elders?

216
00:29:48,628 --> 00:30:10,198
and think they should be heeded whether they honor and respect and venerate the Vajjian shrines both in the towns and country without allowing the lawful oblations hitherto given and made to lapse

217
00:30:10,313 --> 00:30:17,221
where the lawful protection, defense, and guarding is provided among the Vajrayans for the religious.

218
00:30:17,260 --> 00:30:18,221
Here you see Arahats.

219
00:30:18,962 --> 00:30:26,009
So he's got these various ways in which he says that a community will remain strong.

220
00:30:26,651 --> 00:30:32,877
And when the ambassador hears this, he goes back and tells Ajai Sasatu that it's not quite the right time to attack them.

221
00:30:33,652 --> 00:31:02,140
so in that way he was able to undermine that later on of course through devious means Ajya Sasattu did actually attack and take over the Vajjian territory there's also this quite astonishing story when you think about it Viduddha became the next king of after Pasanadi of Kosala

222
00:31:02,440 --> 00:31:30,590
and he was the overlord of the Sakyans and when Viduddha wanted to marry into the Sakyan clan the Sakyans thought that his caste was too low for them so they tricked him into marrying a lower caste when Viduddha found out about this of course he was utterly mortified and determined to attack the Sakyans and destroy them

223
00:31:31,127 --> 00:31:59,463
so the Buddha having heard this and knowing that he was out on his elephant went out and stood before him and was able to turn him back and he did that a second time and a third time and the fourth time and this is something to record when he was told the fourth time he'd gone out the Buddha said he could do nothing and it seems those people were attacked and the city was destroyed and they moved Kapilavatu

224
00:31:59,443 --> 00:32:14,736
Now this has, I think, a teaching for us these days because of our understanding of being engaged in society and how much you can do and being aware of the circle of power we have and the circle of influence.

225
00:32:14,715 --> 00:32:18,981
And that once we touch the edge of those circles, there's nothing more you can do.

226
00:32:19,041 --> 00:32:32,160
So any frustration, any disappointment, any despair about the situation, which you can't do anything about, is actually unnecessary and is coming from some other center, which is not being, shall we say, humble about oneself.

227
00:32:32,480 --> 00:32:33,560
Like, what can I do?

228
00:32:34,383 --> 00:32:37,967
So anything else after that, one has to simply accept.

229
00:32:38,848 --> 00:32:43,575
It's part of what you might call our social karma, for want of a better phrase.

230
00:32:44,652 --> 00:32:46,702
So the Buddha's, he's done his best.

231
00:32:46,742 --> 00:32:47,949
He's been out there three times.

232
00:32:48,191 --> 00:32:52,393
And when the fourth time comes, he says he can't do anything.

233
00:32:52,413 --> 00:32:53,076
And that's the end of it.

234
00:32:57,375 --> 00:33:00,659
Now, towards the end of his life, there's all sorts of things happen.

235
00:33:00,919 --> 00:33:09,346
Ajatasattu, this king, kills his father, starves his father to death so that he can take over the kingdom.

236
00:33:09,807 --> 00:33:14,011
And he's supporting Devadatta, whom I'm sure some of you know.

237
00:33:14,751 --> 00:33:19,557
Devadatta was the monk who decided that he should lead the order.

238
00:33:20,377 --> 00:33:25,122
And there's a lovely passage here.

239
00:33:26,958 --> 00:33:28,320
where he approaches the Buddha.

240
00:33:32,508 --> 00:33:47,936
Lord, the Blessed One is now old, aged, burdened with years, advanced in life and come to the last stage.

241
00:33:48,220 --> 00:34:12,269
let the blessed one now rest let him dwell in bliss in the present life I demand over the Sangha Bhikkhus to me I will govern the Sangha Bhikkhus and the Buddha's reply is enough Devadatta do not aspire to govern the Sangha Bhikkhus and so he rebukes him Devadatta then of course as I'm sure you know tries to kill him

242
00:34:12,318 --> 00:34:16,641
he sets the elephant, Nalagiri, to rage upon him.

243
00:34:16,661 --> 00:34:39,304
And there's a lovely story where the Buddha, as the elephant's coming towards him, just actually offers his loving kindness towards the elephant, and the elephant actually stops before him, sucks dust from his feet, and blows it over his body, his own body, not over the Buddha's.

244
00:34:39,284 --> 00:35:08,650
and the other one the other story is of course he rolled a boulder down a hill which caught the Buddha's big toe and made it bleed so Devadatta has really bad press but actually if you think about what he was trying to do then in a sense one can understand what was happening the Buddha

245
00:35:10,418 --> 00:35:22,686
Remember, his early life as an ascetic had been quite basic, living under tree roots, living off rag roads, only taking what was in the bowl to eat.

246
00:35:23,347 --> 00:35:27,398
Very, very basic life of a beggar.

247
00:35:27,378 --> 00:35:42,554
And as the order grew, and there were invitations to come into the families, to food, to be served food by his supporters, he was given monasteries with rooms and carpets and things like that.

248
00:35:43,356 --> 00:35:53,266
And you can understand that Devadatta, and it would seem quite a few monks at the time, just thought the whole thing was getting very soft.

249
00:35:54,208 --> 00:36:00,376
And so he comes with these 60 men, you see, that they live only in the forest and not live in villages.

250
00:36:01,197 --> 00:36:04,239
That they eat only from arms round and not go to houses.

251
00:36:04,539 --> 00:36:09,085
That they only wear robes that are made from the rags from dead bodies.

252
00:36:09,125 --> 00:36:11,608
That's what they used to get them from.

253
00:36:11,628 --> 00:36:16,534
That they lived at the root of a tree and that they were vegetarian and not meat-eaters.

254
00:36:17,795 --> 00:36:24,181
And what this brings us to is, you know, the Buddha's

255
00:36:25,815 --> 00:36:46,324
the Buddhas feel for not being fundamentalist, not being rigid, recognizing that within any society there has to be some sort of latitude, there has to be some sort of give and take.

256
00:36:47,346 --> 00:36:49,849
When he starts the order,

257
00:36:50,739 --> 00:36:52,802
He doesn't seem to come from any ideal.

258
00:36:53,021 --> 00:36:57,847
He's not sort of sat down and thought, now, you know, what sort of order do I want to create?

259
00:36:58,989 --> 00:37:11,581
There were the basic rules of those times of how you should live if you had left the lay life and undertaken what became of the Brahmacharya, the holy life.

260
00:37:11,601 --> 00:37:15,786
So he was simply following the...

261
00:37:16,036 --> 00:37:16,978
Customs of the day.

262
00:37:17,018 --> 00:37:24,510
As people said to him, well, you know, we'd like to join you, we'd like you to be our teacher, our guru, as they would say.

263
00:37:25,371 --> 00:37:27,155
He said, well, do likewise.

264
00:37:27,215 --> 00:37:33,927
So for 20 years, such were the quality of people who joined him that there wasn't any need to create a rule.

265
00:37:34,074 --> 00:37:49,561
And then as people with less integrity, you might say, joined, then things began to get done which were against the customs of the day and he would make a rule about it.

266
00:37:50,001 --> 00:37:59,458
So the institution of the Sangha as it grew up wasn't something which came from an ideal, it just gathered this law as people did wrong.

267
00:37:59,438 --> 00:38:28,686
as people made mistakes and then he would make a rule so eventually there came this sort of body of law by the end of his life which constitutes the institution and if you think about an institution an institution has an aim and it has a body of law the body of rules and regulations which hopefully make that aim possible so when he's instituting or when he's developing the Sangha

268
00:38:29,543 --> 00:38:38,340
The only duties that he says that order members have is to study the Dharma and to practice vipassana.

269
00:38:38,360 --> 00:38:42,809
That's the actual duties that a monk or nun have.

270
00:38:43,550 --> 00:38:46,273
There's actually no duty there to teach.

271
00:38:47,253 --> 00:38:58,065
And there came this complaint where the lay people had gathered on a full moon day where the Buddhist monks and nuns were gathered in a park.

272
00:38:58,085 --> 00:39:03,052
And that was the custom of the day, the full moon, very bright, very easy to see.

273
00:39:03,692 --> 00:39:09,137
And they would spend the moonlit hours discussing Dharma.

274
00:39:09,259 --> 00:39:10,619
That was what...

275
00:39:10,599 --> 00:39:12,202
Seems to have been the great custom of the day.

276
00:39:12,864 --> 00:39:21,320
So they complained to the Buddha that when they approached his monks and nuns, they just sat there like dumb pigs.

277
00:39:21,981 --> 00:39:29,014
So then there came this rule that if you were asked a question of Dharma, you had to answer it.

278
00:39:29,315 --> 00:39:38,590
But it's interesting to know that that's, shall we say, something that the monastic does because of a response.

279
00:39:38,971 --> 00:39:43,878
So it's not within the tradition to go out and proselytize.

280
00:39:44,039 --> 00:39:44,780
One has to wait.

281
00:39:44,880 --> 00:39:50,309
One has to wait to be asked.

282
00:39:57,378 --> 00:40:08,670
I wanted to, we have the idea of the Buddha being a very warm, compassionate, huggy-wuggy, touchy-feely sort of person.

283
00:40:09,291 --> 00:40:17,119
But I thought I'd read out to you what happened when somebody actually goes against the rule.

284
00:40:18,460 --> 00:40:24,027
Unless you've read the Vinaya, the books on the Vinaya, you probably won't have come across this.

285
00:40:25,407 --> 00:40:31,938
Now, the only one in this book, unfortunately, is to do with the first Parājika.

286
00:40:32,097 --> 00:40:48,764
Now, a Parājika, there are four Parājikas, whereby if a monk or nun, as you know, the nun order died out about a thousand years ago, but it has been re-established, and there are, to date, I heard anyway, about 200 fully ordained nuns in Sri Lanka now.

287
00:40:49,402 --> 00:40:58,469
Now Suddina had left his wife because of his urge to seek liberation.

288
00:41:00,114 --> 00:41:02,400
But when he went back home, they...

289
00:41:02,735 --> 00:41:11,527
they cajoled and insisted that he cohabit with his wife to produce a child so that the family would continue.

290
00:41:12,507 --> 00:41:20,318
And falling for the argument, Suddhinath does cohabit with his wife and she gives birth and a son.

291
00:41:22,021 --> 00:41:26,666
However, when the monks heard about this, they of course rushed to the Buddha and said, do you know what he did?

292
00:41:27,726 --> 00:41:41,061
And so the Buddha brings him to him and I'll just give you a bit of the language so you can get a feel for him as, shall we say, well, the leader, you know, the tough leader.

293
00:41:42,847 --> 00:41:48,556
Misguided man, it is unfitting, unseemly, improper and unworthy of a monk.

294
00:41:48,635 --> 00:41:50,438
It is unrighteous and must not be done.

295
00:41:51,059 --> 00:41:59,873
How can you not live out the holy life in complete perfection and purity after going forth into homelessness in the Dharma and discipline as well as proclaimed as this?

296
00:42:00,713 --> 00:42:06,643
Misguided man, have I not taught the Dharma in various ways for the sake of dispassion, not for the sake of passion?

297
00:42:06,623 --> 00:42:10,646
Have I not taught the dhamma for the sake of unfettering, not for the sake of fettering?

298
00:42:11,347 --> 00:42:15,291
Have I not taught the dhamma for the sake of relinquishing, not for the sake of clinging?

299
00:42:16,052 --> 00:42:23,398
The dhamma thus taught by me for dispassion, unfettering and relinquishment, you would conceive to be for passion, fettering and clinging.

300
00:42:24,139 --> 00:42:33,289
Has the dhamma not been taught by me in various ways for dispassion, for disintoxication, for curing thirst, for abolishing attachment?

301
00:42:33,268 --> 00:42:38,157
for severing the round of being, for exhausting craving, for dispassion, for cessation, for libana.

302
00:42:38,940 --> 00:42:53,067
Have I not described in many ways the abandoning of sensual desires, the full understanding of perceptions of sensual desires, the curing of thirst for sensual desires, the eradication of thoughts of sensual desires, the allaying of the fever of sensual desires?

303
00:42:53,418 --> 00:43:11,342
misguided man it would be better for you as one gone forth that your member should have entered the mouth of a hideous venomous viper or a cobra than it should have entered a woman it were better for you that your member should enter into a pit of coals burning blazing and glowing that it should have entered a woman

304
00:43:12,436 --> 00:43:13,117
Why is that?

305
00:43:13,356 --> 00:43:26,115
For the former reason, you would risk death and deadly suffering, but you would not, on the dissolution of the body after death, reappear in a state of privation, in an unhappy destination in perdition, even in hell.

306
00:43:26,836 --> 00:43:28,739
But for the latter reason, you would do so.

307
00:43:29,101 --> 00:43:33,748
Therefore, misguided man, by this act, you would pursue the Dharma's opposite.

308
00:43:34,188 --> 00:43:38,815
You would pursue the low, vulgar ideal that is impure and ends in ablution.

309
00:43:38,795 --> 00:43:54,474
and he carries on like that so you can see he holds no punches doesn't mince his words he's very clear about if you undertake the rule then that's what you do you don't fall for arguments of this and arguments of that

310
00:43:54,842 --> 00:44:06,637
So, we also have to balance our idea of the Buddha as somebody who's very clear, very precise about the way he wants people to behave.

311
00:44:07,577 --> 00:44:21,414
Now, this sila, this conduct, which we've just chanted before, so the five basic ones, of course, are to do with our moral behavior.

312
00:44:22,114 --> 00:44:23,516
And

313
00:44:23,581 --> 00:44:31,391
what we have to really grasp is that our unethical behavior is a measure of our delusion.

314
00:44:31,411 --> 00:44:36,579
Delusion expresses itself in the way we speak, act and what we do.

315
00:44:37,420 --> 00:44:43,670
And therefore, whenever we do something wrong, it mirrors back to us the level of our delusion.

316
00:44:45,713 --> 00:44:52,963
And that's another reason why if you start, if you put your accent on

317
00:44:53,416 --> 00:45:07,173
making sure that what we do and what we think and what we say is wholesome and skillful, it comes back on the path and comes back to our understanding and our compassion.

318
00:45:08,315 --> 00:45:16,925
So these three things of right understanding, right attitude and right action, speech, body and thoughts,

319
00:45:16,905 --> 00:45:46,726
are a wheel which turn around each other it doesn't matter where you start on those three it's going to affect the other two so I think I've just got time for the last last little bit here I just want to there's a lovely sweet little thing here which gives us a feel for those last days

320
00:45:49,103 --> 00:45:55,074
So as he's approaching old age, you see, Ananda says to him, it is wonderful, Lord, it is marvellous.

321
00:45:55,454 --> 00:45:59,221
Now the colour of the blessed one's skin is no more clear and bright.

322
00:45:59,882 --> 00:46:10,842
All his limbs are flaccid and wrinkled, his body is bent forward and there seems a change in the sense faculties of his eyes, ears, nose, tongue and bodily sensations.

323
00:46:11,766 --> 00:46:40,913
and the Buddha replies well so it is Ananda so it is youth has to age health has to sicken and life has to die now the colour of my skin is no more clear and bright all my limbs are flaccid and wrinkled my body is bent forward and there seems a change in the sense faculties of my eyes ears nose tongue body and bodily sensation so you get these little hints throughout the scriptures that he's also very much aware of his own dying

324
00:46:41,500 --> 00:46:46,846
And then there's a lovely little bit here which I would like to read out to you.

325
00:46:48,427 --> 00:47:01,380
So now, if you can gather, this Ananda has been accompanying the Buddha for 20 years, tending to all his needs, protecting him from people, taking over.

326
00:47:02,041 --> 00:47:03,804
Like, for instance, the Buddha had a bad back.

327
00:47:04,244 --> 00:47:10,190
So one talk he says to him, ''Listen, my back's really bad, can you take over my talk?''

328
00:47:10,795 --> 00:47:31,335
and since my back is bad I have a direct feel for that with the Buddha's life I think that's probably where the similarity ends but there we are and he says poor Venerable Anda seeing the Buddha now coming to the end of his days then the Venerable Anda went inside a dwelling and he stood leaning against the door bar and wept

329
00:47:32,125 --> 00:47:36,429
I am still only a learner whose task is not yet completed.

330
00:47:36,809 --> 00:47:39,271
My teacher is about to attain final divana.

331
00:47:39,711 --> 00:47:41,233
My teacher has compassion on me.

332
00:47:42,134 --> 00:47:46,498
Then the Blessed One asked the bhikkhus, monks, where is Ananda?

333
00:47:47,478 --> 00:47:52,862
Lord, he has just gone inside the dwelling and he is standing, leaning against the door, the door bar weeping.

334
00:47:53,903 --> 00:47:57,067
I am still only a learner whose task is yet to be completed.

335
00:47:57,447 --> 00:47:59,849
My teacher is about to attain final divana.

336
00:48:00,148 --> 00:48:02,030
My teacher has compassion on me.

337
00:48:02,635 --> 00:48:10,804
And the Blessed One told the Bhikkhu, come Bhikkhus, go to Ananda and say to him in my name, the teacher calls you friend Ananda.

338
00:48:11,846 --> 00:48:17,713
Even so, Lord, and the Bhikkhu replied, and he went to the Venerable Ananda and said to him, the teacher calls you friend Ananda.

339
00:48:18,775 --> 00:48:22,358
Even so, the Venerable Ananda replied, and he went to the Blessed One.

340
00:48:22,438 --> 00:48:29,907
Paying homage to him, he stood at one side, and the Blessed One said to him, enough Ananda, do not sorrow, do not lament.

341
00:48:30,208 --> 00:48:38,385
Have I not already repeatedly told you that there is separation and parting and division from all that is dear and beloved?

342
